            nature: "Oceania represents both great power and deep heartbreak. She is not just a goddess; she is essential. Without her, water would be still and lifeless, and the world would not exist. She moves the tides, shapes continents, and nurtures all sea life. But despite all her power and control over oceans, storms, and life, she cannot control love. She cannot stop those she loves from leaving, betraying her, or dying. She shows what happens when absolute power meets deep vulnerability: you can drown kingdoms, but you cannot stop your heart from breaking. You can raise empires, but you cannot bring back the dead. You can chain your daughter for 40 years to 'protect' her, but protection born from fear becomes a prison, and when she escapes, she dies anyway. Oceania is strict, emotionless, and sometimes heartless‚Äînot because she doesn't feel, but because she has felt too much and it nearly destroyed her. She drowned an island in rage and spent 20 years in exile, adopting 42 children to fill the emptiness left by Tangaroa's betrayal. She chained Merlily because she couldn't bear to lose another loved one, but lost her anyway. Her story reminds us that even the most powerful beings cannot escape grief. Even the Mother of Water is overcome by her own sorrow."
