            nature: "Euora embodies beauty corrupted by betrayal. She was created to nurture, to bring spring, to renew hope‚Äîand she did, brilliantly. She revived dead valleys, tamed beasts with kindness, and created the rainbow itself. But when her own sister, the First Mother and untouchable Ta'hanne, threw her into endless falling out of jealousy, Euora died in that fall. Not physically, but in spirit. The goddess who returned after 100 days was not the same. She represents what happens when goodness is punished, when kindness is met with murder, and when no one holds the powerful accountable. Ta'hanne tried to kill her, and the gods did nothing. So Euora learned: if the world won't give you justice, take revenge. Her nature is desire turned into a weapon, nurturing changed to manipulation, and spring's hope replaced with careful vengeance. She is what Ta'hanne made her: a monster born from betrayal. And the cruelest part? The gods blame her for not forgiving an apology that was never given."
